SIMPLE: shifter
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shifter
<hw>Shift"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who,
or that which, shifts; one who plays tricks or practices artifice; a
cozener.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T was such a <qex>shifter</qex> that, if truth were known,⟦br⟧
Death was half glad when he had got him down.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>An assistant to the ship's cook
in washing, steeping, and shifting the salt provisions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>An arrangement for
shifting a belt sidewise from one pulley to another.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<fld>(Knitting Mach.)</fld> <def>A wire for changing a loop from one
needle to another, as in narrowing, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(construction, tunneling)</fld> <def>A foreman
responsible for the work on one shift in one area, as in one
heading{4}.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>RH</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shiftiness</ent>⟦br⟧
